post_text:
GOOD NEWS!
Re-Entry dates have not changed! Grades K-2 are still starting back to school on September 8th and Grades 3-5 are still starting back to school on September 15th.

However, in order to comply with the state's "Hybrid" Model,
Students will be in-person learning on Tuesdays, Wednesdays, and Thursdays ONLY Fridays must remain Remote Learning at home.

**Please note**
Students considered to be in the at-risk categories:
K-3 and/or students with disabilities (Special Education)
can still come to school for extra help on Fridays making sure to stay at a 5:1 ratio-
5 students per one teacher.
Please call to make an appointment with the school and/or teacher.

CMS looks forward to seeing all K-2 students on Tuesday!

Have a Safe and Happy Labor Day Weekend!

ATTENTION: GREAT NEWS! The US Department of Agriculture (USDA) will extend federal waivers across the country so that we can serve free meals to ALL children throughout the fall months!
This will help us to ensure that no matter what the situation is on-the-ground - our children have access to nutritious food as the country recovers from the COVID-19 pandemic.

Now, our students will have one less thing to worry about as they adjust to evolving in-school and remote learning situations!

**Note: Those students who will still be on the Remote Learning Model MUST continue to email Ms. Ardia with the next week's meal (breakfast & lunch) orders. Please include your name(s), grade level, and contact information**

If a childâ€™s question is chosen, parents or guardians will be invited to record the child asking it for playback during a Facebook Live event in September (details to come).

The idea for the event sprang from a comment to the governor by a member of New Mexicoâ€™s Economic Recovery Council that her 7-year-old son thought the world was ending. Gov. Lujan Grisham called the boy, answered his questions, and came away wanting to offer answers to other New Mexico children.

Dear Cloudcroft Families,

Thank you for bearing with us as we work through our Internet issues. Students are now able to get onto their Canvas to complete assignments. Yesterday's assignments will not be counted late, and students will not be counted absent for not attending a live session.
Teachers have recorded yesterday's lessons and will have them on their Canvas pages for students to watch.
For the remainder of the week, teachers will record their lesson to accompany their assignments.
Teachers will check Canvas for student log-in to take attendance.
Next week, we plan to have our live classrooms in session. For those who need the Proxy server info the user name is studentcb and the password is bearscb. Again thank you for your patience on this matter. Have great evening.

F.Y.I.
Stimulus Checks
Please help us spread the word that families in your school or district may be owed thousands of dollars in unclaimed federal stimulus checks. These checks, if delivered and spent, could offset hardship and boost local economies. About 124,000 mostly low-income New Mexicans have have until Oct. 15 to file a tax return or complete an online IRS form to trigger release of their checks. The funding is provided through the federal CARES Act. This flier has more information on the importance of the stimulus check for families.
https://drive.google.com/file/d/19bPaPcQGRfSQ8R_aqILnkgKSx22ab-bv/view

Just released this morning from the Governor's Facebook page (Governor MichelleLujan Grisham)- please view the link below for more detailed information:

My administration made the very difficult decision, in close consultation with educational and health leaders, to extend public school closures through the rest of the academic year. We have to continue to take very aggressive steps to mitigate the spread of COVID-19.

We know this has tremendous implications for families and students all across the state. This is part of a two-pronged plan my administration is crafting to protect New Mexicans from COVID-19 and ensure that children are protected, fed and educated and that families are supported through this crisis.

We are in unprecedented times. Public health is our first and foremost priority. We will keep doing everything we can to keep kids, teachers, families and workers all across the state safe from this terrible virus.

Find more information about the closure extension here: https://bit.ly/3butL57

Follow the New Mexico Public Education Department on Facebook.

post_text:
Statement from New Mexico Public Education Department:

"The new Public Health Order issued yesterday does not affect the Public School Closure Period, but an extended closure is likely. We know that you are eagerly awaiting an update and it is our intention to give you as much notice as possible to make plans. As Governor Michelle Lujan Grisham said during the press conference yesterday, "We are working with the federal government-- what waivers need to be in place, what we do about graduations, what we do about college applications, what we do about distance learning and support, how can we assure every student has the same access to that level of learning, which is an important requirement for rural states like this one." We anticipate making an announcement later this week or early next week."

In an effort to try to provide food to all of our students that are in need, Cloudcroft Municipal Schools will be delivering breakfast/lunch combo grab-n-go meals to OUR communities during Tuesday, March 17 - Friday, March, 20 and Tuesday, March 31 - Friday, April 3.

Our distribution schedules and locations are as follows:
Mayhill Post Office: 10:00 - 10:30 am
Weed Post Office: 11:00 - 11:30 am
Timberon Post Office: 10:30 - 11:00 am

We will be using our schools' suburbans for distribution.

Also during those dates, we will still be providing the grab-n-go breakfast/lunch combo meals at the Cloudcroft High School south kitchen entrance from 9:30 am - 12:00 pm.

We are trying to provide the best convenience for our families - whichever locations work best for them.

Please feel free to contact the school at (575)601-4416 for more information or concerns.

After discussions between NMPED and the NMAA, all High School track meets are postponed until further notice. With the Middle Schools short season, the Cloudcroft Middle School track season has been cancelled. If your student athlete is an 8th grader, they are still eligible to run at the high school level. Contact coach Adams or Coach Preslar for more information about what paperwork needs to be filled out for your 8th grader to run at the HS level.
We are sorry for the inconvenience and especially disappointed for our Middle School Athletes. We are following what has been passed down to us.
text:
After discussions between NMPED and the NMAA, all High School track meets are postponed until further notice. With the Middle Schools short season, the Cloudcroft Middle School track season has been cancelled. If your student athlete is an 8th grader, they are still eligible to run at the high school level. Contact coach Adams or Coach Preslar for more information about what paperwork needs to be filled out for your 8th grader to run at the HS level.
We are sorry for the inconvenience and especially disappointed for our Middle School Athletes. We are following what has been passed down to us.
